<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-328-664  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 328 664.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  March 29 1990 v35 n7 p107(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mass storage: part 2. (includes related articles on CAM: a commonaccess method for SCSI, DMA controllers, and what was left out ofthe All-Star PC)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leibson, Steven H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mass-storage capacity for microcomputers has vastly improved sincethe early IBM PC.andP;  EDN magazine's ideal microcomputer, labelledthe All-Star PC, would incorporate eight mass-storage peripheraldevices managed by three controller or host-adapter cards thatwould provide flexible information storage and easy datainterchange among microcomputers.andP;  Each of the mass-storagesubsystems provide unique capabilities: the floppy-disk systemswould support four floppy-disk drives, providing removable datastorage and permitting standardized data interchange with othermicrocomputers; the SCSI subsystem controls two 330Mbyte harddisks for primary data-storage needs and a 2.5Gbyte tape unit forarchival and backup storage; and the optical WORM drive providesindelible file storage on 1Gbyte cartridges.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Memory ManagementMass MemoryStorage MediaMicrocomputersDirectories.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   (Three subsystems provide the All-Star PC's mass-storagecapabilities). (chart)Compaticard IV floppy-disk formats. (table)(Stats for various EDN PC All-Stars). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>